The Battle of Neighborhoods Final Report¶

1. Introduction:¶

Brazil is the country with the largest number of Japanese immigrants, and, as such, has a big affinity with japanese food and culture. Now, let's say that you are a tourist in the beautiful Country of Brazil, and want to go to the city in which you can better explore and taste the fusion of those two very different cultures. The target audience is people who are interested in coming to Brazil and exploring its vast immigration history.

2. Data:¶

For the project, we will need population data and Japanese immigration data, so that we can see which states have had the biggest japanese influence. With this information we will then choose the 6 cities that seem to most likely have had some kind of japanese influence and use the Foursquare API to map the Japanese restaurants and see which location will contain a higher number of Japanese restaurants.

3. Selecting cities:¶

We need to select the cities in which we will do our analysis. To do so we take the brazilian state capitals with the largest number of Japanese immigrants. According to IBGE (Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics) the 6 state capitals with the biggest number of Japanese Brazilians are Curitiba, So Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, Campo Grande, Braslia and Belm do Par. You can read the study here . Unfortunately there doesn't seem to be data from after 2000, but we will make do.

4. Methodology:¶

We will try to find which city has the higher density of Japanese Restaurants. We use the foursquare data to map the restaurants, iterate the request in the 6 cities, find a center coordinate of the venues and then use euclidean distance to see which city is the best. We will plot each map and see ourselves the location of each Restaurant. Unfortunately the Foursquare API has a limit of 100 locations per city, so the analysis won't be as correct as we would like. The indicator, thus, will be mean distance from mean coordinate.

Now we map the locations. Afterwards we will calculate the density of each city.

6. Discussion:¶

It looks like Campo Grande has the lowest mean distance from mean coordinates, which means that it has a higher density of Japanese Restaurants. OF course, the higher scores of So Paulo and Rio de Janeiro speak to the difficulty of making such comparisons. Because of the size of the two cities, only a smaller number of restaurants could be shown from the cities and as such, the results ended up being more sparse. The project has a meaning, but unfortunately it's incomplete due to Foursquare API limitations.

7. Conclusion:¶

We decided to calculate the density of Japanese Restaurants on each city, and It looks like Campo Grande and Curitiba are the best for that. We used euclidean distance to calculate the center coordinate, which would also be the perfect place to book an hotel if you want to be as near as pollible to the highest number of Japanese Restaurants. So, if you decide to come to Brazil and want to experience the Japanese Immigrant culture, you know where to go!
